    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## 7. TRAIN-TEST SPLIT\n",
    "\n",
    "### What is Train-Test Split?\n",
    "\n",
    "Train-test split divides the dataset into two parts:\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Training Set (80%):** Used to train the machine learning model\n",
    "- **Testing Set (20%):** Used to evaluate the model's performance on unseen data\n",
    "\n",
    "### Why is it Necessary?\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **Prevents Overfitting:** If we train and test on the same data, the model will memorize the data instead of learning patterns\n",
    "2. **Realistic Evaluation:** Testing on unseen data gives a true measure of model performance\n",
    "3. **Generalization:** Helps ensure the model can work on new, unknown data in the real world\n",
    "4. **Fair Comparison:** Allows us to compare different models fairly\n",
    "\n",
    "### Parameters Used:\n",
    "- **test_size=0.2:** 20% of data for testing, 80% for training\n",
    "- **random_state=42:** Ensures reproducibility (same split every time)\n",
    "- **stratify=y:** Maintains the same proportion of each class in both sets"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Split the data into training and testing sets\n",
    "X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(\n",
    "    X,  # Features\n",
    "    y,  # Target\n",
    "    test_size=0.2,  # 20% for testing, 80% for training\n",
    "    random_state=42,  # For reproducibility\n",
    "    stratify=y  # Maintain class distribution\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"=\"*70)\n",
    "print(\"TRAIN-TEST SPLIT RESULTS\")\n",
    "print(\"=\"*70)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"\\nOriginal dataset size: {X.shape[0]} samples\")\n",
    "print(f\"Training set size: {X_train.shape[0]} samples ({X_train.shape[0]/X.shape[0]*100:.1f}%)\")\n",
    "print(f\"Testing set size: {X_test.shape[0]} samples ({X_test.shape[0]/X.shape[0]*100:.1f}%)\")\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"\\n\" + \"-\"*70)\n",
    "print(\"TRAINING SET DETAILS\")\n",
    "print(\"-\"*70)\n",
    "print(f\"Shape of X_train: {X_train.shape}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Shape of y_train: {y_train.shape}\")\n",
    "print(f\"\\nClass distribution in training set:\")\n",
    "print(y_train.value_counts())\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"\\n\" + \"-\"*70)\n",
    "print(\"TESTING SET DETAILS\")\n",
    "print(\"-\"*70)\n",
    "print(f\"Shape of X_test: {X_test.shape}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Shape of y_test: {y_test.shape}\")\n",
    "print(f\"\\nClass distribution in testing set:\")\n",
    "print(y_test.value_counts())\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"\\n\" + \"=\"*70)\n",
    "print(\"✓ Data successfully split into training and testing sets!\")\n",
    "print(\"=\"*70)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Feature Scaling (Optional but Recommended)\n",
    "\n",
    "For KNN, it's important to scale features because KNN uses distance calculations. Features with larger ranges can dominate the distance calculation."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Scale the features using StandardScaler\n",
    "# This is important for KNN because it uses distance metrics\n",
    "scaler = StandardScaler()\n",
    "\n",
    "# Fit the scaler on training data and transform it\n",
    "X_train_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Transform the testing data using the same scaler\n",
    "X_test_scaled = scaler.transform(X_test)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"=\"*70)\n",
    "print(\"FEATURE SCALING\")\n",
    "print(\"=\"*70)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"\\n✓ Features have been scaled using StandardScaler\")\n",
    "print(\"\\nWhy scale features for KNN?\")\n",
    "print(\"- KNN calculates distances between data points\")\n",
    "print(\"- Features with larger ranges can dominate the calculation\")\n",
    "print(\"- Scaling ensures all features contribute equally\")\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"\\nBefore scaling (first 5 samples of training data):\")\n",
    "print(X_train.head())\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"\\nAfter scaling (first 5 samples of training data):\")\n",
    "print(pd.DataFrame(X_train_scaled[:5], columns=X_train.columns))\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"\\nMean of scaled features (should be ~0):\")\n",
    "print(X_train_scaled.mean(axis=0).round(4))\n",
    "\n",
