    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## 8. MODEL BUILDING - K-NEAREST NEIGHBORS (KNN)\n",
    "\n",
    "### What is K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN)?\n",
    "\n",
    "KNN is a simple, intuitive machine learning algorithm that classifies data points based on the classes of their nearest neighbors.\n",
    "\n",
    "### How KNN Works:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **Calculate Distance:** Compute the distance between the query point and all training points\n",
    "2. **Find K Nearest:** Select the K closest points to the query point\n",
    "3. **Count Classes:** Count the class labels of these K neighbors\n",
    "4. **Predict:** Assign the class with the most votes to the query point\n",
    "\n",
    "### Advantages of KNN:\n",
    "- Simple and easy to understand\n",
    "- No training phase (lazy learner)\n",
    "- Works well for small to medium-sized datasets\n",
    "- Effective for multi-class classification\n",
    "\n",
    "### Disadvantages of KNN:\n",
    "- Computationally expensive for large datasets\n",
    "- Sensitive to feature scaling\n",
    "- Requires careful selection of K\n",
    "- Memory-intensive\n",
    "\n",
    "### Parameter: n_neighbors=3\n",
    "We're using K=3, meaning each prediction is based on the 3 nearest neighbors. This is a good starting point for balanced datasets."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Create a KNN classifier with n_neighbors=3\n",
    "knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=3)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Train the model using the scaled training data\n",
    "knn.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train)\n",
